               <h2>Diet</h2>
                
            </div>
            
            <div class = 'beginner-weights'>
                <div class = 'weight-info'>
                	<p>
                    	Diets another highly controversial and contested subject! A subject I believe has been made overly complicated due
                        to how popular and lucrative it is to reinvent the wheel. Before looking at diets and worrying about a plan of action
                        it is crucial to work out what your goals are! Do you want to lose some fat? gain some lean muscle? What time frame
                        do you have? The scope of diets is so large I can only give basic advice for now. The following is assuming you are
                        healthy and doing some form of exercises. As always consult your doctor about your health. 
                    </p>
                    
                    <h2>Calories</h2>
                    <p>
                    	Got your goal in mind? Good!(What do you mean NO!!) Next we need to find out how much calories you are using.
                       	I actually created a tool on this site to use, it's a BMR (Basel Metabolic Rate) calculator. You will need to be
                        logged in to use it however <a href = '/profiles/tools#bmr'>BMR Link</a> If you cant use my one, just do a google search
                        for BMR should be no problem.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	Your BMR is the amount of calories you use just by being alive, if you lay in bed all day and didnt move a muscle,
                        it would be close to your BMR. However we dont lay in bed all day (alas my student days!) so it is not accurate enough
                        yet. If you're hardcore and know each activities calorie usage you can add it to the BMR, but for the rest of us we can
                        just multiple it by general activity level. 
                    </p>
                    
                    <ul>
                        <li>If you are sedentary (little or no exercise) : Calorie-Calculation = BMR x 1.2</li>
                        <li>If you are lightly active (light exercise/sports 1-3 days/week) : Calorie-Calculation = BMR x 1.375</li>
                        <li>If you are moderatetely active (moderate exercise/sports 3-5 days/week) : Calorie-Calculation = BMR x 1.55</li>
                        <li>If you are very active (hard exercise/sports 6-7 days a week) : Calorie-Calculation = BMR x 1.725</li>
                        <li>If you are extra active (very hard exercise/sports & physical job or 2x training) : Calorie-Calculation = BMR x 1.9</li>
                    </ul>
 
                    <p>So for me my BMR is 1958 calories, and I workout 3 days a week so I'll be cautious and pick the second level 1.375</p>
                    
                    <p>So 1958 * 1.375 = 2692 calories. This is the amount of calories I need to eat to maintain my current weight</p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	But I'm feeling a bit chunky and want to lose some fat, I'm not in much of a rush so I only want to lose 1lb (0.45kg) 
                    	a week
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	<strong>3500 Calories =  1lb of fat.</strong> So if I cut my calories by 500 a day, 500 * 7 = 3500.
                        By eating 2692 - 500 (2192) calories a day I will be meeting my goal.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	Hopfully I have given you guys the insight into what you need to do to get your calories sorted. I would just
                        note that everyones different and theres no hard and fast rules, I look at these numbers as guidelines. If
                        for example you are -500 calories a day on your needed amount, but still arent loosing weight then dont be afraid
                        to try -600 or -700 until you get the result you want. However dont lose weight too fast as it can be dangerous
                        and dont bulk too hard are you'll just end up fat (Speaking from many delicious experiences!)  
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	For more information <a href = 'http://www.bmi-calculator.net/bmr-calculator/harris-benedict-equation/'>Link</a>
                    </p>
                    
                    <h2>Macros</h2>
                    
                    <p>
                    	<strong>Protein:</strong> Protein is a nutrient needed by the human body for growth and maintenance. 
                        Aside from water, proteins are the most abundant kind of molecules in the body. 
                        Protein can be found in all cells of the body and is the major structural component of all cells in the body, 
                        especially muscle.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	<strong>Carbohydrates:</strong> Foods high in carbohydrate include fruits, sweets, soft drinks, breads, pastas, beans, 
                    	potatoes, bran, rice, and cereals. Carbohydrates are a common source of energy in living organisms; however, 
                    	no carbohydrate is an essential nutrient in humans.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	<strong>Fat: </strong>Fats play a vital role in maintaining healthy skin and hair, insulating body organs against shock, 
                        maintaining body temperature, and promoting healthy cell function.

						Fats also serve as energy stores for the body, containing about 37.8 kilojoules (9 calories) per gram of fat.
                        They are broken down in the body to release glycerol and free fatty acids. The glycerol can be converted 
                        to glucose by the liver and thus used as a source of energy.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	<strong>Fibre: </strong>Advantages of consuming fiber are the production of healthful compounds 
                        during the fermentation of soluble fiber, and insoluble fiber's ability (via its passive 
                        hygroscopic properties) to increase bulk, soften stool, and shorten transit time through the intestinal tract.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	Source and more information see <a href = 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/'>Wikipedia</a>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	Ok got the general information of the macros of nutrition out of the way. We can now talk about how
                        we can use our calorie allowance to be the most efficent for us. The breakdown of macros is a much
                        discussed topic, the popular atkins diet uses something like 50% protein 0% carbs 50% fat for example.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	You can get very complicated with regards to macro breakdown and food timings but I personnally like
                        to keep things simple. and basically do the following.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	<strong>Get 1 gram of protein per lb of bodyweight </strong> I weigh 95kgs(CHUNKY MONKEY) which I convert to lbs
                        95 * 2.2 = 209lbs. So I want to get about 209 grams of protein a day and will aim to do so.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	<strong>Get over 20 grams of fibre </strong> An often overlooked yet important rule! This will make sure you dont
                        have....."issues" when dieting and is important for general sanity and health
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	and thats all folks! For the carbs and fat I just wing it as long as I'm getting my protein and fibre and stay within
                        my calories for the day things will go well.
                        
                        I should mention that not all foods are created equal so drinking 100 grams
                        of carbs as Coke a Cola wont be as good or nutritious as 100 grams of carbs in brown bread.
                        Just keep things clean and sensible and you'll be grand.
                    </p>
                    
                    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
                    <p>
                    	Alot of information covered here. I hope it's clear and helps some people get an idea of how to plan and execute a
                        successful diet. In many ways this is the easy part putting it into practice is where things get difficult. I do
                        Believe diet information in general is overly complicated and losing or gaining weight is pretty simple, if you eat
                        more than you need you'll gain weight if you eat less than you need you'll lose weight, easy. Good luck guys!
                    </p>
                </div>
