                <div class = 'weight-info'>
                	<p>
                    	Some of my pros and cons might be a bit controversial, I'll prempt any question marks. HIIT is "suppose to boost
                        metabolism" The reason I say "Suppose" is because I personnaly could not confirm this but it's generally accepted HIIT
                        does do this. "Fitness didnt improve much" this might just be me but I could never seem to improve my fitness, everyday
                        I came to do my thing I seemed to struggle at the same point everytime and my speed was much the same. 
                        "Requires decent starting fitness" HIIT stands for high intensity interval training, so if you're doing running,
                        this will require sprinting which if you're really unfit you might struggle with and cause injury. 
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	HIIT has you doing high intensity for say 30-40 seconds then moderate for 10-20 seconds and you continue
                        this pattern for about 20 minutes. For me what I did was walk the width of a football pitch and sprint(frail widely)
                        the length. It's pretty good fun atleast at the start near the end of 20 mins....not so fun. 
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	I cant really recommend HIIT for newbies, the high intensity could cause injury and theres no real sense
                        of progression you'd find in a routine like couch to 5k. Like most things it comes down to what your goal
                        actually is. If looking to get fit then i'd look elsewhere, but if you want just add some exercise to lose
                        some weight in a time efficient way HIIT could be worth trying.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                    	For more information <a href = 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High-intensity_interval_training'>Link</a>
                    </p>
